      <abstract id="6f2019a4-3722-4322-8f06-88aeb62ceeff">
        <label>Abstract</label>
        <p>Flies in the family <tp:taxon-name><tp:taxon-name-part taxon-name-part-type="family">Milichiidae</tp:taxon-name-part></tp:taxon-name> are often myrmecophilic. We document the first record of a fly from this family interacting with an ant of the genus <italic><tp:taxon-name><tp:taxon-name-part taxon-name-part-type="genus">Polyrhachis</tp:taxon-name-part></tp:taxon-name></italic>. In lowland riparian rainforest in Sabah, Malaysia, we observed a female of the genus <italic><tp:taxon-name><tp:taxon-name-part taxon-name-part-type="genus">Milichia</tp:taxon-name-part></tp:taxon-name></italic> following an ant of the species of <italic><tp:taxon-name><tp:taxon-name-part taxon-name-part-type="genus">P.</tp:taxon-name-part> <tp:taxon-name-part taxon-name-part-type="species">illaudata</tp:taxon-name-part></tp:taxon-name></italic>, and repeatedly attempting to make close contact. Our observation suggests that the dipteran may have been attempting to feed kleptoparasitically from the <italic><tp:taxon-name><tp:taxon-name-part taxon-name-part-type="genus">Polyrhachis</tp:taxon-name-part></tp:taxon-name></italic> worker, since members of this ant genus often feed on liquid carbohydrate-rich food resources. This is the first time an interaction has been observed between a fly of this family and an ant of this widespread old world tropical genus.</p>
      </abstract>
